<font color="#FF0000">TOO YOUNG TO UNDERSTAND</font><br>
<tt>Thu May  1 13:47:01 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I was born in 1968, so I don't know how my father was before the war, but I have heard from family members.  Last New Year's Eve my father told me how much he regrets the way our relationship has gone.  He told me that he had no business having children at that time because after Nam, everything seemed so trivial.  He closed himself off emotionally to me. I thought my whole life that he didn't like or love me.  Now he says it is too late to change our relationship.  I obviously cannot imagine the hell he saw and experienced, but my life has been deeply affected by his experiences.  I am not using this as an excuse, I am a college graduate and have buily myself a decent life, but I still cry very often for the father I had and the daddy I didn't have. No abuse, just a lack of feeling.  Vets, little girls need their Daddy, and it's only too late when you're dead. My dad won't try but I'm sure ther are many others like us.  Love your kids, and let them love you...and thank you 
<p><code>-- johara@electrotex.com  (Staci Hill ) </code><p>


